snippet.textDisplay:
I love and use glass dip pens. Usually when you buy factory-made ones (like the one you have), the nib can be slightly rough/uneven, which might explain the odd dragging sensation you’re feeling. Using sandpaper or a nail file will help. Just lightly sand the very tip, but not too much! Even better is sand it a little, test it, and see if it needs more. There may still be a little dragging, but it’ll glide a lot easier hopefully. There are a few handmade dip pens over on Etsy, and usually their makers already test their pens and make sure this is already taken care of.

Another thing is use India inks for your glass pen. They dry a bit faster in my experience, and the ink still lasts a great amount of time on the nib when writing/drawing. Only con is the India inks have shellac, which can sometimes stick to the grooves, so you’re gonna probably need to clean it a little more often (just some water or alcohol and a paper towel) than you probably were doing here, even if you’re using the same color. It’s slightly tedious, but to me it’s worth it in the end.

I hope this helps you or anyone else who reads this! 😁

snippet.textDisplay:
Ooooh that's cool you discovered the glass pen! I use it sometimes when I make ink illustration and I think using this pen ONLY for the line and only with ink isn't the best way to use all the capacity of this.
Personaly, the thing I love with ink is the way that it can make such beautiful shade in contact of the water (or other liquid tool like other ink or posca for example) so I think this tool is perfect for details or do things that would be difficult to do with a brush. That could be interesting if you can experiment to mix the use of ink (with a brush and glass pen) with other things that can react with ink and make a cool illustation!
(Hope my english isn't too broken haha)
snippet.textOriginal:
